{"result": "**##**(\"entity\"<|>\"David Dawson\"<|>\"examples\"<|>\"David Dawson is an experienced technical consultant who is prepared to work overtime on a new project. He will work on the new project on Monday and Tuesday and catch up with the 10 hours missed on his existing project the following weekend. David is paid a standard hourly rate of $50 and double time (i.e. $100 an hour) for weekend work.\")**##**(\"entity\"<|>\"Freelance technical consultant\"<|>\"examples\"<|>\"A freelance technical consultant is available and charges $75 an hour.\")**##**(\"entity\"<|>\"Edward Eaves\"<|>\"examples\"<|>\"Edward Eaves is an analyst who would be required for 10 hours to document the new client's system. All analysts are busy next week, but a small project on which Edward was due to work can be cancelled, which would enable Edward to work on the documentation for the new client. If the other contract is cancelled, a contribution of $1,000 would be lost. Edward is paid an hourly rate of $50.\")**##**(\"entity\"<|>\"Relevant cost of project manager\"<|>\"concepts\"<|>\"The relevant cost of the project manager is zero because Bill Bates, who will manage the new project next week, is paid a fixed salary and has spare time next week. Therefore, there is no additional cost to the company for Bill to manage this project.\")**##**(\"entity\"<|>\"Relevant cost of business consultant\"<|>\"concepts\"<|>\"The relevant cost of the business consultant would be the $5,000 discount given to the other client for agreeing to delay the training course by a week. Colin would have to be taken off a training course, but since he can deliver it a week later, the contribution from that course is not lost, so it is not relevant. Colin is also on a fixed salary, so will not be paid extra for working on the project.\")**##**(\"entity\"<|>\"Relevant cost of technical consultant\"<|>\"concepts\"<|>\"There is a choice between using the internal technical consultant, David Dawson, or an external consultant. The cost of the external consultant would be $750 (i.e. $75 an hour for 10 hours). If David were to be used, he would have to work overtime. Although the overtime rate of $100 would be incurred while working on his existing project, that overtime rate would only be paid if he were used on the new project, so the cost of using David is $100 an hour. Therefore, as the external consultant is the cheaper option, the relevant cost would be $750.\")**##**(\"entity\"<|>\"Relevant cost of analyst\"<|>\"concepts\"<|>\"The relevant cost is $1,500, which is the direct cost of Edward's time ($50 * 10) plus the opportunity cost of $1,000. The direct cost of Edward's time is relevant because he is paid an hourly wage of $50, a variable cost. The opportunity cost is the lost contribution on the other project that Edward would have worked on.\")**##**(\"entity\"<|>\"Non-current assets\"<|>\"concepts\"<|>\"Non-current assets, such as machinery, may be required for a contract. The relevant cost of such assets depends on how the organization plans to obtain the use of it: If the asset is to be rented (or hired), the rental costs over the period of use are relevant. If the asset is to be acquired (purchased) for the contract, the cost of acquiring the asset (including related costs, such as delivery and installation) would be relevant. It may be that when the contract is completed, the asset can be sold. In this case, the expected proceeds from the sale will be relevant income that should be deducted from the total cost of acquiring the asset when calculating the relevant cost. An asset such as the one that is required may already be owned. The relevant cost then depends on whether that asset is already operating at full capacity on other activities. If the asset is not used for other purposes (or has spare capacity), the relevant cost is the fall in realisable value that will arise if the asset is used for the contract. If the asset is already operating at full capacity, its relevant cost is its deprival value.\")**##**(\"entity\"<|>\"Fall in Realisable Value\"<|>\"concepts\"<|>\"Fall in realisable value refers to the decrease in the value of an asset if it is used for a specific contract instead of being sold immediately. For example, if Bob, a builder, owns a crane that he could sell today for $150,000 but decides to use it for a contract, and the crane's value falls to $120,000 after the contract, the fall in realisable value is $30,000.\")**##**(\"entity\"<|>\"Deprival Value\"<|>\"concepts\"<|>\"Deprival value is the cost of depriving the business of an asset that is already owned but currently fully utilized in other activities. It is determined by considering the 'value in use' and the 'replacement cost' of the asset. Value in use is the higher of its net realisable value and its economic value. Economic value is the present value of the future earnings that the asset would generate for the business.\")**##**(\"entity\"<|>\"Value in use\"<|>\"concepts\"<|>\"Value in use is the value to the business of an asset that is already owned. It is the higher of its net realisable value (the net amount that would be realized if it was disposed of) and its economic value (the present value of the future earnings that the asset would generate for the business).\")**##**(\"entity\"<|>\"Replacement cost\"<|>\"concepts\"<|>\"Replacement cost is the cost of acquiring a new asset to replace an existing one. It is considered when determining the deprival value of an asset that is already owned but currently fully utilized in other activities.\")**##**(\"relationship\"<|>\"David Dawson\"<|>\"Relevant cost of technical consultant\"<|>\"David Dawson is an example used to explain the relevant cost of a technical consultant.\"<|>8)**##**(\"relationship\"<|>\"Freelance technical consultant\"<|>\"Relevant cost of technical consultant\"<|>\"Freelance technical consultant is an example used to explain the relevant cost of a technical consultant.\"<|>8)**#